SIMPLE: fend
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fend
<hw>Fend</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fiend.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fend</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fend
<hw>Fend</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Fended</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Abbrev. fr.
<ets>defend</ets>.]</ety> <def>To keep off; to prevent from entering or
hitting; to ward off; to shut out; -- often with <xex>off</xex>; <as>as,
to <ex>fend</ex> off blows</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With fern beneath to <qex>fend</qex> the bitter cold.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To fend off a boat</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To
fend off a vessel</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to prevent
its running against anything with too much violence.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fend</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fend
<hw>Fend</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To act on the defensive, or in
opposition; to resist; to parry; to shift off.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The dexterous management of terms, and being able to
<qex>fend</qex> . . . with them, passes for a great part of
learning.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fender</ent>⟦br⟧
